Giao linh shirt-White-Medium-Unisex,,Fashion,simple,"Default Category,Default Category/Viet Nam,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion/Traditional Costumes",base,"Giao linh shirt-White-Medium-Unisex","<div data-content-type=""html"" data-appearance=""default"" data-element=""main""><style>

The Áo Giao Lĩnh is a traditional Vietnamese garment that is often favored and worn during important events and festivals. It also served as the formal attire for Vietnamese women during the Ly dynasty, showcasing its elegance and prestige throughout Vietnam's fashion history.

In addition, the Áo Giao Lĩnh shares similarities with some traditional garments of other East Asian countries, such as the Kimono of Japan and the Hanbok of Korea. From the unique feature of its crossed-collar design, the Áo Giao Lĩnh has played a significant role in the diversity and distinctive style of traditional Vietnamese attire.

The Áo Giao Lĩnh is a traditional Vietnamese garment that is often favored and worn during important events and festivals. It also served as the formal attire for Vietnamese women during the Ly dynasty, showcasing its elegance and prestige throughout Vietnam's fashion history.

In addition, the Áo Giao Lĩnh shares similarities with some traditional garments of other East Asian countries, such as the Kimono of Japan and the Hanbok of Korea. From the unique feature of its crossed-collar design, the Áo Giao Lĩnh has played a significant role in the diversity and distinctive style of traditional Vietnamese attire.

Việt phục (Vietnamese traditional costume) is one of the distinctive cultural symbols of Vietnam, represented through various types of traditional attire that are diverse and rich. Each type of attire carries its own historical, cultural, and aesthetic values, contributing to the vibrant cultural landscape of the nation.
Việt phục has undergone many ups and downs throughout history, influenced by feudal dynasties and cultural exchanges with neighboring countries.
• Northern domination period: Clothing was influenced by Chinese culture, characterized by garments such as the ""áo giao lĩnh"" (cross-collared robe), long trousers, dresses, and hats.
• Independent period: Việt phục flourished with unique attire such as the ""áo ngũ thân"" (five-panel dress), ""áo dài"" (long dress), ""yếm"" (cross-over garment), and ""nón lá"" (conical hat).
• French colonial period: Clothing was influenced by Western culture, resulting in a combination of traditional and modern attire.
• Present day: Việt phục is preserved and promoted through traditional festivals, cultural events, and everyday life.
Diverse and rich styles, reflecting historical and cultural values
Worn during traditional festivals, cultural events, and special occasions

Each type of attire carries its own historical, cultural, and aesthetic values, contributing to the vibrant cultural landscape of the nation.
Việt phục has undergone many ups and downs throughout history, influenced by feudal dynasties and cultural exchanges with neighboring countries.
• Northern domination period: Clothing was influenced by Chinese culture, characterized by garments such as the ""áo giao lĩnh"" (cross-collared robe), long trousers, dresses, and hats.
• Independent period: Việt phục flourished with unique attire such as the ""áo ngũ thân"" (five-panel dress), ""áo dài"" (long dress), ""yếm"" (cross-over garment), and ""nón lá"" (conical hat).
• French colonial period: Clothing was influenced by Western culture, resulting in a combination of traditional and modern attire.
• Present day: Việt phục is preserved and promoted through traditional festivals, cultural events, and everyday life.

Việt phục (Vietnamese traditional costume) is one of the distinctive cultural symbols of Vietnam, represented through various types of traditional attire that are diverse and rich. Each type of attire carries its own historical, cultural, and aesthetic values, contributing to the vibrant cultural landscape of the nation.
Việt phục has undergone many ups and downs throughout history, influenced by feudal dynasties and cultural exchanges with neighboring countries.
• Northern domination period: Clothing was influenced by Chinese culture, characterized by garments such as the ""áo giao lĩnh"" (cross-collared robe), long trousers, dresses, and hats.
• Independent period: Việt phục flourished with unique attire such as the ""áo ngũ thân"" (five-panel dress), ""áo dài"" (long dress), ""yếm"" (cross-over garment), and ""nón lá"" (conical hat).
• French colonial period: Clothing was influenced by Western culture, resulting in a combination of traditional and modern attire.
• Present day: Việt phục is preserved and promoted through traditional festivals, cultural events, and everyday life.
Diverse and rich styles, reflecting historical and cultural values
Worn during traditional festivals, cultural events, and special occasions

Pieu scarf-Red,,Fashion,simple,"Default Category,Default Category/Viet Nam,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion/Items",base,"Pieu scarf-Red","<div data-content-type=""html"" data-appearance=""default"" data-element=""main""><style>

Pieu Scarf (or ""Pieu"") is one of the distinctive cultural symbols of the Thai people, especially the Black Thai ethnic group. The scarf not only serves as a decorative item but also carries significant cultural and spiritual values, being an indispensable part of the lives of Thai women.
• Style: Pieu Scarf is approximately 1.5 - 2 meters long and 30 - 40 cm wide. The two ends of the scarf are embroidered with vibrant patterns, each carrying unique symbolic meanings.
• Material: Hand-woven brocade fabric, typically made of silk or silk yarn.
• Colors: Rich and diverse, predominantly red, blue, yellow, and purple.
• Patterns: Abundant, featuring common motifs such as dragon-phoenix patterns, geometric patterns, and floral motifs.
• Material: Hand-woven brocade fabric (silk or silk yarn)
• Colors: Various, including red, blue, yellow, and purple

Today, Pieu Scarf continues to be used in traditional festivals, cultural events, and daily life of the Thai people. The scarf is a beautiful symbol, adding to the diverse cultural landscape of Vietnam.

Pieu Scarf (or ""Pieu"") is one of the distinctive cultural symbols of the Thai people, especially the Black Thai ethnic group. The scarf not only serves as a decorative item but also carries significant cultural and spiritual values, being an indispensable part of the lives of Thai women.
• Style: Pieu Scarf is approximately 1.5 - 2 meters long and 30 - 40 cm wide. The two ends of the scarf are embroidered with vibrant patterns, each carrying unique symbolic meanings.
• Material: Hand-woven brocade fabric, typically made of silk or silk yarn.
• Colors: Rich and diverse, predominantly red, blue, yellow, and purple.
• Patterns: Abundant, featuring common motifs such as dragon-phoenix patterns, geometric patterns, and floral motifs.
• Material: Hand-woven brocade fabric (silk or silk yarn)
• Colors: Various, including red, blue, yellow, and purple

Today, Pieu Scarf continues to be used in traditional festivals, cultural events, and daily life of the Thai people. The scarf is a beautiful symbol, adding to the diverse cultural landscape of Vietnam.

column1: Traditional Vietnamese wedding attire-Red-Large-Unisex,,Fashion,simple,"Default Category,Default Category/Viet Nam,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion,Default Category/Viet Nam/Fashion/Traditional Costumes",base,"Traditional Vietnamese wedding attire-Red-Large-Unisex","<div data-content-type=""html"" data-appearance=""default"" data-element=""main""><style>

Vietnamese traditional attire, with its flowing ao dai for the bride and elegant ao ngu than for the groom, is a symbol of the grace, sophistication, and refinement of Vietnamese culture. Soft materials, intricate patterns, and meticulous tailoring enhance the graceful and charming beauty of Vietnamese women.
Reasons to Wear Traditional Attire on Wedding Day:
• Express National Pride: Wearing traditional clothing on this important day is a way to express national pride, honoring and cherishing the traditional cultural values.
• Creating Uniqueness: Traditional attire adds uniqueness and distinction to the wedding day, leaving a lasting impression on guests.
• Preserving Meaningful Moments: Adorning oneself in traditional attire on the wedding day is a way to preserve meaningful moments, contributing to the creation of a wedding rich in ethnic identity.
Traditional Vietnamese attire is not just clothing
column2: it is also a symbol of culture and tradition. Choosing traditional attire for the wedding day is a way to express national pride, preserve meaningful moments, and create a unique and distinctive wedding celebration.

The patterns and motifs on Mong ethnic clothing are rich in color. They combine warm colors to create a striking and impressive appearance. Without focusing too much on patterns, the designs on Mong ethnic dresses involve color combinations, as well as interweaving and changing materials through smooth patches (patchwork), raised patches (embroidery), or details that make the decorative art on Mong ethnic clothing truly unique and distinctive compared to other ethnic groups.
Perfect for cultural events, ceremonies, and special occasions
